Variable Transformations

Ryan Miller

The Need for Transformation

  • The variables recorded in a dataset aren’t always conducive to an informative visualization or a statistically valid analysis
    • This presentation will cover 3 strategies for transforming variables to yield more useful and/or more interpretable results
    • These strategies are: log-transformations, standardization (centering and rescaling), and discretization

Log Transformations

  • Right-skewed variables are common, and they can be problematic for both visualizations and statistical methods that use normality assumptions
  • Shown below are data on 53,940 diamonds sold by an online retailer
    • Question: How can you tell that both of the variables depicted are right-skewed?

Log Transformations

  • Taking the logarithm of a variable can alleviate right-skew (and reduce the impact of outliers) while retaining interpretability
    • A 1-unit increase in the \(log_2(carat)\) is a doubling in carat, a nifty interpretation
    • On the \(log_2\) scale, we see a clear linear relationship between “Carat” and “Price”

Log Transformations

  • Recall that linear regression operates under the assumption the residuals are approximately normally distributed
    • If we model “Price” using “Caret” this assumption is violated
    • But, the assumption is reasonable if we transform each variable using a base-2 logarithm

Interpreting Log-Transformed Variables

  • The log-transformation is simple and interpretable, recall:
    • A 1 unit increase in the variable log2_carat is a doubling in carat
    • A 1 unit increase in the variable log2_price is a doubling in price
  • Question: How would you interpret the effect of “Lot Area” in each of the plots shown below?

Interpreting Log-Transformed Variables - Solution

  • In Plot #1, a doubling of lot area (a 1-unit increase on the log2-scale) is expected to increase a home’s price by $ 75.3k
  • In Plot #2, a doubling of lot area (a 1-unit increase on the log2-scale) is expected to increase a home’s price by a factor of \(2^0.45\), or a 36.6% increase in price

Standardization

  • Suppose we want to know whether lot area of the number of bedrooms has larger impact on a home’s sale price
  • We could use simple linear regression slopes to summarize the impact of each variable on sale price (in thousands)
    • The coefficient of lot area (acres) is 239.5
    • The coefficient of bedrooms is 45.6
  • Question: Which variable has a greater impact?

Standardization

  • A 1 acre increase in lot area isn’t comparable with a 1 bedroom increase, so these slopes don’t tell us which variable has a larger impact
  • A better approach would compare the effect of a 1 standard deviation increase in each variable
    • In R, the scale function will center and standardize a variable, thereby transforming its original values to z-scores
    • We can refit our models using the standardized versions of “bedrooms” and “lot area”. Now we see that lot area has a slightly larger impact with a 1 standard deviation increase leading to an expected increase in sale price of $46,590
y <- data$sale.amount/1000
x1 <- scale(data$area.lot)
x2 <- scale(data$bedrooms)

lm(y ~ x1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x1)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)           x1  
##      180.10        46.59
lm(y ~ x2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x2)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)           x2  
##      180.10        45.21

Discretization

  • The final type of transformation we’ll discuss today is discretization, or consolidating a numeric variable into discrete ordinal categories
  • To motivate discretization, we’ll look at the survival of passengers on the Titanic by age
    • Question: How does age relate to survival? Who’s more likely to survive, a 5 year-old or a 25 year-old? How about a 25 year-old, a 45 year-old, or 65 year-old?

Discretization

  • The impact of age is drastic at young ages, we see that children under age 10 were much more likely to survive than adults
  • However, among adults there doesn’t appear to be much difference in survival
    • We might consider splitting age into young children (ages 12 and under) and older children plus adults (ages 13 and older) using the cut function
    • This simplifies the data, while retaining the important information from the original variable
data$age_discrete = cut(data$age, breaks = c(0,12,99))

When to Consider Discretization

  • Discretization makes sense when your original data doesn’t have a linear relationship, and instead contains meaningful groups (ie: infants, children, adults) with similar outcomes
  • Discretization can lead to a substantial loss of information when you do have a smooth relationship between explanatory and response variable
  • Discretization can also be useful in trying to express complex multivariate relationships in a single visualization, as plots can be faceted (stratified) or colored using categorical values

Example of Multivariate Relationship

Takeaways

  • Consider a log-transformation when skew or outliers make it difficult to effectively utilize a variable
  • Consider standardization when seeking to understand or compare variables with different scales (units)
  • Consider discretization when it can simplify a numeric variable for analysis or visualization without a loss of information
  • Always keep the Simple-to-Complex principle in mind, avoid transformations that complicate your analysis without a clear benefit
